MALE SPEAKER: All right.

00:01:29.200 --> 00:01:31.400
So before we jump into
the book, let's first talk

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:32.880
about kind of your journey.

00:01:32.880 --> 00:01:35.290
You started out working in
the restaurant/bar industry.

00:01:35.290 --> 00:01:38.010
He even ran Barney's Beanery,
which most people here

00:01:38.010 --> 00:01:38.780
know about.

00:01:38.780 --> 00:01:41.194
And then you went into
the consulting business.

00:01:41.194 --> 00:01:43.110
Can you kind of talk
about that transformation

00:01:43.110 --> 00:01:46.372
from working and owning bars to
moving into being a consultant?

00:01:46.372 --> 00:01:47.080
JON TAFFER: Sure.

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:48.570
I didn't learn this in college.

00:01:48.570 --> 00:01:50.530
I was a political science major.

00:01:50.530 --> 00:01:52.930
Very glad I didn't go into
that business, by the way.

00:01:52.930 --> 00:01:54.950
But I started tending
bar in college.

00:01:54.950 --> 00:01:56.250
And one thing led to another.

00:01:56.250 --> 00:01:58.040
And as Jon Lennon
once said "life

00:01:58.040 --> 00:02:00.450
is what happens when
you make other plans."

00:02:00.450 --> 00:02:02.360
And I wound up being
in the bar business

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:04.970
and started as a bartender.

00:02:04.970 --> 00:02:07.300
Became a head bartender,
assistant manager,

00:02:07.300 --> 00:02:09.030
general manager.

00:02:09.030 --> 00:02:10.660
Moved into the hotel arena.

00:02:10.660 --> 00:02:13.140
Became a general manager
of a large resort,

00:02:13.140 --> 00:02:15.960
and vice president
of a hotel company.

00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:19.460
And in the mid-'80s,
tax codes changed.

00:02:19.460 --> 00:02:22.780
And hotels couldn't
write off the deductions

00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:23.840
that they used to.

00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:27.280
So suddenly, restaurants and
hotels had to make money.

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:29.140
They couldn't be
write-offs anymore.

00:02:29.140 --> 00:02:30.860
And the hotel
industry had operated

00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:34.230
what I call guest
amenities, not businesses.

00:02:34.230 --> 00:02:35.100
So I came in.

00:02:35.100 --> 00:02:37.040
And I'm that guy
who signed contracts

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:38.731
with all the big
hotel companies.

00:02:38.731 --> 00:02:40.480
I'm the guy who closed
all the restaurants

00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:42.880
in the top of hotels
all across the country.

00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:43.850
Shut them all down.

00:02:43.850 --> 00:02:46.650
I'm the first guy who ever put
a leased restaurant in a Holiday

00:02:46.650 --> 00:02:49.790
Inn hotel, which was a
very good idea for them,

00:02:49.790 --> 00:02:53.780
and really worked very deeply
bringing brands into hotels

00:02:53.780 --> 00:02:56.410
and working in hotel food
and beverage when I started.

00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:59.950
I wound up doing about 300
hotels all over the world.

00:02:59.950 --> 00:03:04.160
Properties like the Park Hyatt
in Sydney, Grand Hyatt Tokyo,

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:07.370
Taipei, Taiwan,
Jerusalem, London,

00:03:07.370 --> 00:03:10.410
and started working all over the
world for the hotel industry.

00:03:10.410 --> 00:03:14.080
And my whole purpose
was to teach hoteliers

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:15.710
how to do restaurants
and bars that

00:03:15.710 --> 00:03:17.820
could compete against
free standing.

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:19.970
Because in those days,
hotels had no credibility

00:03:19.970 --> 00:03:21.160
in that arena.

00:03:21.160 --> 00:03:22.680
And that's how I started.

00:03:22.680 --> 00:03:26.380
And I started my
consulting company in 1986.

00:03:26.380 --> 00:03:29.560
And my first client was the
company that I worked for.

00:03:29.560 --> 00:03:31.510
So I left, brought them in.

00:03:31.510 --> 00:03:35.810
And then my life changed
when Sheraton came up to me

00:03:35.810 --> 00:03:37.540
and offered me a major contract.

00:03:37.540 --> 00:03:40.320
And I did 40 Sheraton hotels.

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:43.000
And out of the 40 that I
did, if I remember correctly,

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:46.930
18 of them had the highest sales
per foot in food and beverage

00:03:46.930 --> 00:03:49.120
in the entire hotel industry.

00:03:49.120 --> 00:03:50.720
And then it all took off for me.

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:52.780
Then, my phone started
ringing off the hook.

00:03:52.780 --> 00:03:55.970
In 1991, I opened my first--
actually, that's not correct.

00:03:55.970 --> 00:03:59.660
In 1989, I opened the first
operation that I ever owned.

00:03:59.660 --> 00:04:01.430
Any Green Bay fans here?

00:04:01.430 --> 00:04:02.880
Green Bay Packer fans?

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:05.730
First bar I ever owned was
called Lynn Dickey's Sports

00:04:05.730 --> 00:04:08.750
Cafe, who was a quarterback
for Green Bay back then.

00:04:08.750 --> 00:04:11.040
And I wound up having
three of those.

00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:12.540
And what really
changed my life was

00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:15.170
Mall of America in
Minneapolis, which

00:04:15.170 --> 00:04:17.430
has more visitations than
the city of Las Vegas.

00:04:17.430 --> 00:04:19.980
I opened three restaurants
in Mall of America.

00:04:19.980 --> 00:04:24.240
The landlord gave me all the
money-- I opened them for free

00:04:24.240 --> 00:04:26.770
and two years later,
was a multimillionaire.

00:04:26.770 --> 00:04:28.840
And that really changed my life.

00:04:28.840 --> 00:04:33.320
And I'm inspired not by
the bricks and mortar.

00:04:33.320 --> 00:04:35.890
I'm not inspired
by the food, even

00:04:35.890 --> 00:04:37.160
though it's very important.

00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:39.720
I'm inspired by the
look on your face.

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:42.420
That's always been
my inspiration.

00:04:42.420 --> 00:04:44.930
I don't believe
that we serve food.

00:04:44.930 --> 00:04:46.310
I believe we serve reactions.

00:04:46.310 --> 00:04:48.120
We achieve it through food.

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:49.480
I don't believe we play music.

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:50.420
We play reactions.

00:04:50.420 --> 00:04:51.620
We achieve it through food.

00:04:51.620 --> 00:04:54.030
And I don't believe
you guys sell ads.

00:04:54.030 --> 00:04:58.330
The fact of the matter is if the
viewer doesn't react to the ad,

00:04:58.330 --> 00:04:59.300
the ad is meaningless.

00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:00.070
We don't sell ads.

00:05:00.070 --> 00:05:01.210
We sell reactions.

00:05:01.210 --> 00:05:03.150
We achieve it through
ads, whether they're

00:05:03.150 --> 00:05:06.470
client reactions, whether
they're advertiser reactions

00:05:06.470 --> 00:05:08.300
or prospect reactions.

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:10.410
And that's what I
learned at a young age.

00:05:10.410 --> 00:05:13.940
And that philosophy
changed my life.

00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:15.580
And by understanding
the principle

00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:17.610
of reaction management--
I own that term.

00:05:17.610 --> 00:05:20.570
I actually own the term
"reaction management"--

00:05:20.570 --> 00:05:22.540
everything changed for me.

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:24.590
And suddenly I
realized that wow,

00:05:24.590 --> 00:05:27.080
I can cause you to do things
you wouldn't normally do.

00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:29.837
I can manipulate the hell
out of you if I want to.

00:05:29.837 --> 00:05:30.670
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:05:30.670 --> 00:05:32.169
JON TAFFER: Make
you buy what I want

00:05:32.169 --> 00:05:35.000
you to, go where I want you
to, sit where I want you to.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.340
So I became a nut case
on human behavior.

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:40.400
And things really puzzle me.

00:05:40.400 --> 00:05:44.205
For example, 70% of all
people that walk into a mall

00:05:44.205 --> 00:05:45.275
make a right hand turn.

00:05:45.275 --> 00:05:46.980
Why?

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:47.820
Why?

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:50.983
That -- excuse me--
that shit haunts me.

00:05:50.983 --> 00:05:51.950
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:05:51.950 --> 00:05:52.940
JON TAFFER: It does!

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:56.740
And it makes me say, what can
I do to make you make a left?

00:05:56.740 --> 00:05:59.240
And I will lay awake at
night figuring out ways

00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:00.830
to make you make that left turn.

00:06:00.830 --> 00:06:02.500
And that's very
rewarding to me when

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:04.389
I can change human behavior.

00:06:04.389 --> 00:06:06.680
MALE SPEAKER: Do you think
that's because 90% of people

00:06:06.680 --> 00:06:07.809
are right-handed?

00:06:07.809 --> 00:06:08.850
JON TAFFER: I'm not sure.

00:06:08.850 --> 00:06:09.340
I'm a lefty.

00:06:09.340 --> 00:06:10.548
So I couldn't relate to that.

00:06:10.548 --> 00:06:12.230
But no, I'm not sure that is.

00:06:12.230 --> 00:06:15.660
There's an inherent
movement towards the right.

00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:18.139
Maybe it's because we
bear right on roads.

00:06:18.139 --> 00:06:20.430
Maybe we even bear right when
we walk through airports.

00:06:20.430 --> 00:06:21.730
So maybe that's the principle.

00:06:21.730 --> 00:06:24.700
But it's interesting,
when you go to Asia,

00:06:24.700 --> 00:06:28.350
and they walk into a mall, they
make a right hand turn too.

00:06:28.350 --> 00:06:30.560
So I'm not sure that
argument holds water.

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:33.400
But there are certain
things about human behavior

00:06:33.400 --> 00:06:34.970
that are shocking to me.

00:06:34.970 --> 00:06:38.170
And there's gold, when
you can change behavior.

00:06:38.170 --> 00:06:40.696
Walt Disney was
the master of it.

00:06:40.696 --> 00:06:42.320
You go to Walt Disney
World in Orlando.

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:43.506
It's 120 degrees.

00:06:43.506 --> 00:06:44.630
You're sweating like crazy.

00:06:44.630 --> 00:06:46.569
You spent $90 to walk
through the door.

00:06:46.569 --> 00:06:48.110
Within three minutes,
you're standing

00:06:48.110 --> 00:06:49.810
on line for an hour and a half.

00:06:49.810 --> 00:06:50.310
Right?

00:06:50.310 --> 00:06:52.010
You get off the line, you
go through an attraction

00:06:52.010 --> 00:06:52.676
for two minutes.

00:06:52.676 --> 00:06:55.460
You get on another line
for an hour and a half.

00:06:55.460 --> 00:06:58.190
After three lines in five
hours, you've done three things.

00:06:58.190 --> 00:06:59.560
Now you want a Coke.

00:06:59.560 --> 00:07:01.830
So you stand online for
45 minutes for that.

00:07:01.830 --> 00:07:03.719
Now you get a cup with
Mickey Mouse on it.

00:07:03.719 --> 00:07:06.260
Now you got to carry this thing
around with you all day long.

00:07:06.260 --> 00:07:07.650
$14.95.

00:07:07.650 --> 00:07:11.020
And you realize when you go
home with the bags of stuff

00:07:11.020 --> 00:07:14.280
you'll never use, the
T-shirt you'll never wear,

00:07:14.280 --> 00:07:15.980
you realize wow!

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:20.100
I sweated, I stood in
line, and I loved it.

00:07:20.100 --> 00:07:23.260
And there's a manipulative
quality to business.

00:07:23.260 --> 00:07:24.960
And you're no different.

00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:28.650
When we cause people
to act in ways

00:07:28.650 --> 00:07:32.910
that enhance our objectives,
not theirs, we all make money.

00:07:32.910 --> 00:07:34.550
So the trick is how
do I get you to do

00:07:34.550 --> 00:07:37.230
what isn't natural to you,
but have you love me for it

00:07:37.230 --> 00:07:38.190
in the end?

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:39.510
That's the trick.

00:07:39.510 --> 00:07:41.590
Because I want you to
come back and do it again.

00:07:41.590 --> 00:07:42.090
Right?

00:07:42.090 --> 00:07:45.060
There's no such thing as single
transactions in the world.

00:07:45.060 --> 00:07:47.132
Everything is
multiple transactions.

00:07:47.132 --> 00:07:49.090
I'm all about getting to
that next transaction.

00:07:49.090 --> 00:07:50.340
That's what's important to me.

00:07:50.340 --> 00:07:51.820
MALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:07:51.820 --> 00:07:54.020
So we heard a lot
about your consulting.

00:07:54.020 --> 00:07:57.200
How did the TV show come
about with Spike TV?

00:07:57.200 --> 00:07:58.110
Did you initiate it?

00:07:58.110 --> 00:07:59.220
Did they initiate it?

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:00.140
JON TAFFER: I did.

00:08:00.140 --> 00:08:01.500
I'm very proud of this.

00:08:01.500 --> 00:08:05.004
I've been a public speaker in
my industry for about 30 years.

00:08:05.004 --> 00:08:06.170
And I give keynote speeches.

00:08:06.170 --> 00:08:07.760
And I get a lot of
money for speeches.

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:10.270
I've spoken in about 30
countries around the world.

00:08:10.270 --> 00:08:12.740
And I'll speak in major
industry conventions.

00:08:12.740 --> 00:08:16.730
I'm speaking at Friday's next
week for their corporate event.

00:08:16.730 --> 00:08:19.720
And I was giving a
speech in Las Vegas,

00:08:19.720 --> 00:08:22.540
and somebody came up to me
and said, you should be on TV.

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:23.752
And I thought about it.

00:08:23.752 --> 00:08:25.460
So I went home, and
I wrote something up,

00:08:25.460 --> 00:08:27.930
which was originally
called "On the Rocks."

00:08:27.930 --> 00:08:29.902
And I came out here and
went to Hermosa Beach

00:08:29.902 --> 00:08:31.110
to a friend that owned a bar.

00:08:31.110 --> 00:08:34.590
I got a camera, a microphone,
and I got his employees

00:08:34.590 --> 00:08:35.260
to work with me.

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:37.559
And I did a three
minutes sizzle reel.

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:39.510
And really it was me
just screaming at people.

00:08:39.510 --> 00:08:41.549
I just walked into
his bar, screamed

00:08:41.549 --> 00:08:43.730
and yelled at the employees.

00:08:43.730 --> 00:08:44.420
"Not negotiable!

00:08:44.420 --> 00:08:46.520
You're fired!" and
there's this whole thing.

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:48.830
And I didn't know
anybody in Hollywood.

00:08:48.830 --> 00:08:49.630
I was a bar guy.

00:08:49.630 --> 00:08:52.910
And so I had this three
minutes sizzle reel.

00:08:52.910 --> 00:08:57.490
I sent it cold to five
companies and got three offers--

00:08:57.490 --> 00:08:59.630
and it was unbelievable--
within a week.

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:02.890
And I had offers from three
different production companies.

00:09:02.890 --> 00:09:05.210
So I had a look at each
company, do background checks,

00:09:05.210 --> 00:09:07.570
and the company I picked
was the best one, but not

00:09:07.570 --> 00:09:10.040
necessarily the
best financial deal.

00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:12.430
So I thought more long
term than short term.

00:09:12.430 --> 00:09:15.000
I signed with 3 Ball Productions
in Manhattan Beach, who

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.390
also does "Biggest Loser" and
one of the largest reality

00:09:17.390 --> 00:09:18.770
show producers.

00:09:18.770 --> 00:09:21.600
They picked me up,
signed me to a contract,

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:25.100
and Spike picked up the
show four days later.

00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:28.720
So in the time I got the
idea, to the premiere

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:30.760
of the show on
TV-- not the pilot,

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:33.590
the first season--
was less than a year.

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:35.470
And I'm told that's
almost a record.

00:09:35.470 --> 00:09:38.240
And normally, it takes
two to three years

00:09:38.240 --> 00:09:39.550
to get to that level.

00:09:39.550 --> 00:09:41.164
So I was blessed, I think.

00:09:41.164 --> 00:09:42.080
Some of that's timing.

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:43.290
I get that I'm pretty
good at what I do.

00:09:43.290 --> 00:09:44.200
But some of it is timing.

00:09:44.200 --> 00:09:45.740
I just happened to be in the
right place at the right time,

00:09:45.740 --> 00:09:46.580
I think.

00:09:46.580 --> 00:09:50.080
So the show premiered
almost three years ago.

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:53.665
We just aired our 49th
episode to the highest ratings

00:09:53.665 --> 00:09:54.790
in the history of the show.

00:09:54.790 --> 00:09:55.260
AUDIENCE: [APPLAUSE]

00:09:55.260 --> 00:09:56.176
JON TAFFER: Thank you.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.040
Honestly, it's been an
incredibly humbling experience

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:04.420
for me.

00:10:04.420 --> 00:10:08.336
And I'm shocked when celebrities
get these egos that suddenly

00:10:08.336 --> 00:10:09.460
you're unimportant to them.

00:10:09.460 --> 00:10:10.840
They're above you.

00:10:10.840 --> 00:10:15.040
It has made me appreciate
humanity, the people around me

00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:17.540
that support me, believe in me.

00:10:17.540 --> 00:10:19.365
This has actually made
me a better person.

00:10:19.365 --> 00:10:21.240
And I wouldn't have
thought about it that way

00:10:21.240 --> 00:10:22.540
before the fact.

00:10:22.540 --> 00:10:25.537
But it has humbled me.

00:10:25.537 --> 00:10:27.370
I feel like I'm hugged
by America every day.

00:10:27.370 --> 00:10:29.085
It's an incredible feeling.

00:10:29.085 --> 00:10:30.210
MALE SPEAKER: That's great.

00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:33.850
And so 49 episodes-- how do you
decide which bars to rescue?

00:10:33.850 --> 00:10:35.430
I'm sure you've got
a ton of requests

00:10:35.430 --> 00:10:36.722
from bars all over the country.

00:10:36.722 --> 00:10:38.263
And you've done all
over the country.

00:10:38.263 --> 00:10:39.470
And some are really awful.

00:10:39.470 --> 00:10:41.280
And some are just
horrific, like,

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:42.590
how do you decide which to--

00:10:42.590 --> 00:10:43.943
JON TAFFER: That's my choice.

00:10:43.943 --> 00:10:45.300
Awful or horrific.

00:10:45.300 --> 00:10:46.779
It's pretty accurate too.

00:10:46.779 --> 00:10:49.070
Actually, when I did the
show, my deal with the network

00:10:49.070 --> 00:10:52.470
was I wanted you to find
me the worst in the world.

00:10:52.470 --> 00:10:53.970
I don't want this
to be a cake walk.

00:10:53.970 --> 00:10:55.070
I want to fail.

00:10:55.070 --> 00:10:56.530
I want to fail.

00:10:56.530 --> 00:11:01.350
So now that we're
known, about 1,000 bars

00:11:01.350 --> 00:11:03.220
submit applications
a year for me

00:11:03.220 --> 00:11:06.250
to scream at them,
which is amazing to me.

00:11:06.250 --> 00:11:08.070
And these are people
that are in trouble.

00:11:08.070 --> 00:11:09.790
So we go through a
screening process.

00:11:09.790 --> 00:11:12.410
First of all, we picked the
cities that make sense to us.

00:11:12.410 --> 00:11:14.930
We like small towns, big
towns, Midwest, East Coast.

00:11:14.930 --> 00:11:16.780
We like to move it
around and mix it up,

00:11:16.780 --> 00:11:18.560
so we have the
different subcultures

00:11:18.560 --> 00:11:20.440
of America, if you
will, in a show.

00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:22.420
The next thing we do is
we see if they're real.

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:23.770
Are they hustling
me for a remodel?

00:11:23.770 --> 00:11:24.895
Or are they really in debt?

00:11:24.895 --> 00:11:26.480
Are there really
houses on the line?

00:11:26.480 --> 00:11:27.900
Is this a real story?

00:11:27.900 --> 00:11:29.520
So we verify those elements.

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:31.360
We verify the debt,
all that kind of stuff.

00:11:31.360 --> 00:11:34.080
Make sure that there
are stakes, if you will.

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:38.900
Then, once we've narrowed
it down to about 40 or 50,

00:11:38.900 --> 00:11:40.810
then I'll send a
producer to each

00:11:40.810 --> 00:11:43.990
of those locations with
just a little camera.

00:11:43.990 --> 00:11:47.660
And they'll talk to each staff
member for about 20 seconds.

00:11:47.660 --> 00:11:48.160
That's all.

00:11:48.160 --> 00:11:48.720
What's your name?

00:11:48.720 --> 00:11:49.120
What do you here?

00:11:49.120 --> 00:11:50.520
What do you think of this place?

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:50.950
What's your name?

00:11:50.950 --> 00:11:51.575
What do you do?

00:11:51.575 --> 00:11:55.060
So we can see the
behavior of the employees.

00:11:55.060 --> 00:11:57.230
And I'm looking for
a compelling story,

00:11:57.230 --> 00:12:00.180
I want you rooting for the
owner or hating the owner.

00:12:00.180 --> 00:12:01.900
But I want you connected to it.

00:12:01.900 --> 00:12:06.170
And the secret of "Bar Rescue"
is finding those personalities

00:12:06.170 --> 00:12:07.720
that are exciting to be with.

00:12:07.720 --> 00:12:10.130
And if you think it's
frustrating to watch,

00:12:10.130 --> 00:12:13.290
you should live it, Because
it's quite an experience.

00:12:13.290 --> 00:12:13.790
Very

00:12:13.790 --> 00:12:14.290
MALE SPEAKER: Very cool.

00:12:14.290 --> 00:12:15.956
And what would you
say is the number one

00:12:15.956 --> 00:12:18.160
reason most bars fail.

00:12:18.160 --> 00:12:19.260
JON TAFFER: Excuses.

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:21.980
But that's the reason why
all of you would fail too.

00:12:21.980 --> 00:12:23.080
And here it is.

00:12:23.080 --> 00:12:24.760
You wake up in the morning.

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:25.936
You're failing.

00:12:25.936 --> 00:12:27.060
So you blame the President.

00:12:27.060 --> 00:12:27.880
You blame Congress.

00:12:27.880 --> 00:12:29.080
You blame Greece.

00:12:29.080 --> 00:12:30.410
Blame the Euro.

00:12:30.410 --> 00:12:33.230
I mean, construction
industry-- it's the Mayor!

00:12:33.230 --> 00:12:34.210
Oh, it's the this.

00:12:34.210 --> 00:12:36.700
And you wake up in the morning,
and you look in the mirror.

00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:39.158
And you're not failing, because
it's the other guy's fault.

00:12:39.158 --> 00:12:40.930
Or it's the economy's fault.

00:12:40.930 --> 00:12:42.700
But if you looked in
the mirror and said

00:12:42.700 --> 00:12:45.740
I'm failing because I'm
me, you wouldn't like it.

00:12:45.740 --> 00:12:47.380
And you'd change that.

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:49.300
And I believe the
common denominator

00:12:49.300 --> 00:12:52.420
of failure in any
business is excuses.

00:12:52.420 --> 00:12:55.010
As long as you wake up
and blame poor sales

00:12:55.010 --> 00:12:57.380
on the economy or
an environment, then

00:12:57.380 --> 00:12:59.920
you have no motivation
to make it better,

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:01.600
because it's not your fault.

00:13:01.600 --> 00:13:04.230
But in the worst
economic environment,

00:13:04.230 --> 00:13:06.810
four, five years in this
country, ago, in this country

00:13:06.810 --> 00:13:08.470
that we've seen,
in our lifetimes,

00:13:08.470 --> 00:13:10.847
there were people making a
lot of money, weren't there?

00:13:10.847 --> 00:13:12.430
In the height of
that recession, there

00:13:12.430 --> 00:13:14.750
were people selling advertising,
people opening restaurants,

00:13:14.750 --> 00:13:16.020
people building businesses.

00:13:16.020 --> 00:13:17.510
Somebody's making money.

00:13:17.510 --> 00:13:19.360
So the excuse is bull.

00:13:19.360 --> 00:13:20.550
It's bull.

00:13:20.550 --> 00:13:23.200
So wake up in the morning
and own your failure.

00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:25.480
Look in the mirror and say
I'm failing because of me!

00:13:25.480 --> 00:13:27.210
And you won't like it.

00:13:27.210 --> 00:13:28.700
And then you'll change it.

00:13:28.700 --> 00:13:30.910
But as long as you
don't put it on you,

00:13:30.910 --> 00:13:33.000
you have no motivation
to change it.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.750
So in short, if you
own your failure,

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:37.340
you'll own your success.

00:13:37.340 --> 00:13:40.200
If you don't own your
failure, you'll never dig out.

00:13:40.200 --> 00:13:42.190
And I find that in any business.

00:13:42.190 --> 00:13:44.450
Always the common
denominator of failure,

00:13:44.450 --> 00:13:46.605
personally, is excuses.

00:13:46.605 --> 00:13:48.230
You don't want to be
a failure, do you?

00:13:48.230 --> 00:13:49.070
AUDIENCE: Not at all.

00:13:49.070 --> 00:13:49.490
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:13:49.490 --> 00:13:50.550
JON TAFFER: You don't
want to look in the mirror

00:13:50.550 --> 00:13:52.070
and experience that.

00:13:52.070 --> 00:13:54.150
If you can't blame
anybody but yourself,

00:13:54.150 --> 00:13:55.392
you're going to change.

00:13:55.392 --> 00:13:56.600
You're going to fight it out.

00:13:56.600 --> 00:13:57.550
That's the deal.

00:13:57.550 --> 00:13:58.840
MALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:01.012
So a lot of guys in this
room want to open bars,

00:14:01.012 --> 00:14:02.970
like this one sitting up
here in the front row.

00:14:02.970 --> 00:14:04.862
What do you say to
these people that

00:14:04.862 --> 00:14:06.320
want to open their
own bar one day.

00:14:06.320 --> 00:14:08.110
JON TAFFER: Well, first
of all, know your reason.

00:14:08.110 --> 00:14:10.250
Anybody see the Murphy's
episode of "Bar Rescue"?

00:14:10.250 --> 00:14:12.050
The two frat brothers
opened a bar?

00:14:12.050 --> 00:14:12.460
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:14:12.460 --> 00:14:13.810
JON TAFFER: The last
thing you want to do

00:14:13.810 --> 00:14:15.340
is open a bar because
you like to drink.

00:14:15.340 --> 00:14:16.173
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:14:16.173 --> 00:14:18.120
JON TAFFER: That's like
somebody into drugs

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:19.247
who becomes a pharmacist.

00:14:19.247 --> 00:14:20.080
I mean that's just--

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:21.580
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:14:21.580 --> 00:14:23.240
JON TAFFER: It makes
no sense at all.

00:14:23.240 --> 00:14:24.820
You got do it for
the right reasons.

00:14:24.820 --> 00:14:27.000
You've got to do it because
you love the business.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:28.727
If you love the
social aspect of it,

00:14:28.727 --> 00:14:30.060
you'll never do your financials.

00:14:30.060 --> 00:14:32.240
You'll just hang with
people all day long.

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:34.450
If you love the drinking,
that's even worse.

00:14:34.450 --> 00:14:35.730
You got to love the business.

00:14:35.730 --> 00:14:37.100
It's a tough business.

00:14:37.100 --> 00:14:39.719
And we were talking before we
started, in the clothing store

00:14:39.719 --> 00:14:40.760
business, you buy shirts.

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:42.950
You mark them up 60%, 70%.

00:14:42.950 --> 00:14:44.432
If you got 10
shirts on the shelf,

00:14:44.432 --> 00:14:46.640
you go home that night, you
come back in the morning,

00:14:46.640 --> 00:14:48.010
you still got 10
shirts on a shelf.

00:14:48.010 --> 00:14:48.884
Not the bar business.

00:14:48.884 --> 00:14:52.360
Bar business, you've got
to manage every minute.

00:14:52.360 --> 00:14:53.490
Product is exposed.

00:14:53.490 --> 00:14:54.575
Liabilities are exposed.

00:14:54.575 --> 00:14:56.690
It's a tough business.

00:14:56.690 --> 00:14:58.422
Honestly, if I had
to do it over again,

00:14:58.422 --> 00:15:00.130
I'm not sure I would
be in this business.

00:15:00.130 --> 00:15:02.640
To be honest with you,
when I look at all the work

00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:04.690
that I did over
the years, I could

00:15:04.690 --> 00:15:08.130
have applied those efforts
to bigger things rather than

00:15:08.130 --> 00:15:09.570
smaller bars.

00:15:09.570 --> 00:15:11.830
And I was involved in
Rainforest Cafe, for example.

00:15:11.830 --> 00:15:13.700
That went public, and
it was big dollars.

00:15:13.700 --> 00:15:14.491
Don't get me wrong.

00:15:14.491 --> 00:15:16.560
I don't regret being
in the bar business.

00:15:16.560 --> 00:15:20.350
But when I look at my life,
all the nights that I worked,

00:15:20.350 --> 00:15:22.920
all those evenings,
days, 20-hour days,

00:15:22.920 --> 00:15:25.580
I look back and say gee, wonder
if I would have been a lawyer.

00:15:25.580 --> 00:15:26.637
Nah, maybe not a lawyer.

00:15:26.637 --> 00:15:27.470
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:15:27.470 --> 00:15:28.530
AUDIENCE: No!

00:15:28.530 --> 00:15:31.390
JON TAFFER: There are lifestyles
that are easier is my point.

00:15:31.390 --> 00:15:33.020
So you've got to
love the business

00:15:33.020 --> 00:15:34.590
and be passionate
about it to make it

00:15:34.590 --> 00:15:36.877
through those late nights
and those mornings.

00:15:36.877 --> 00:15:37.710
MALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:15:37.710 --> 00:15:39.480
And what's been the
hardest "Bar Rescue"

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:40.630
you've ever done and why?

00:15:43.160 --> 00:15:45.660
JON TAFFER: I'm going to guess
the hardest "Bar Rescue" I've

00:15:45.660 --> 00:15:49.860
ever done was the one
that aired-- actually,

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:52.590
the last one with
the two twins, which

00:15:52.590 --> 00:15:54.402
aired just about
three weeks ago,

00:15:54.402 --> 00:15:56.110
where I had a family--
I mean, these guys

00:15:56.110 --> 00:15:58.060
hadn't had Christmas dinner
together in nine years.

00:15:58.060 --> 00:16:00.018
They lived across from
each other, these twins,

00:16:00.018 --> 00:16:01.900
and they hated each other.

00:16:01.900 --> 00:16:03.675
And what I learned
about "Bar Rescue"

00:16:03.675 --> 00:16:06.030
is it's so about the people.

00:16:06.030 --> 00:16:08.340
And at the end of the day,
I got those twins together.

00:16:08.340 --> 00:16:09.874
It was a pretty intense episode.

00:16:09.874 --> 00:16:11.290
And I don't know
if any of you saw

00:16:11.290 --> 00:16:14.110
that episode-- the
son Tyler, the nephew,

00:16:14.110 --> 00:16:17.930
sent me a note that they had
their best Christmas dinner

00:16:17.930 --> 00:16:20.120
in all these years
for the family.

00:16:20.120 --> 00:16:23.465
So when you have
personalities that don't work,

00:16:23.465 --> 00:16:24.340
that's the challenge.

00:16:24.340 --> 00:16:25.250
I can paint the bar.

00:16:25.250 --> 00:16:26.570
I know how to set it up.

00:16:26.570 --> 00:16:27.840
I know how to put
the technology in it.

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:28.923
I know how to decorate it.

00:16:28.923 --> 00:16:30.590
I know how to program.

00:16:30.590 --> 00:16:32.619
The people--
remember these people

00:16:32.619 --> 00:16:34.160
aren't failing
because of their bars.

00:16:34.160 --> 00:16:36.410
They're failing because of them.

00:16:36.410 --> 00:16:37.569
And that's my challenge.

00:16:37.569 --> 00:16:39.110
And that was a
particularly good one.

00:16:39.110 --> 00:16:41.193
And I'm going to answer
the next question for you.

00:16:41.193 --> 00:16:43.500
The best one we've
ever done is probably

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:47.020
"Spirits on Bourbon," which was
the first episode this season.

00:16:47.020 --> 00:16:50.180
They're up $125,000 a month.

00:16:50.180 --> 00:16:51.135
AUDIENCE: Holy shit!

00:16:51.135 --> 00:16:52.510
JON TAFFER: The
barber shop chair

00:16:52.510 --> 00:16:55.440
is the most photographed
attraction on Bourbon Street.

00:16:55.440 --> 00:17:00.140
Last month, it did over
$80,000-- just that chair.

00:17:00.140 --> 00:17:01.704
And the guys, they
sent me a note.

00:17:01.704 --> 00:17:02.870
They've become good friends.

00:17:02.870 --> 00:17:05.200
They just bought a
warehouse, so they

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:08.720
can buy cups for their
Resurrection cocktails, 20,000

00:17:08.720 --> 00:17:11.280
at a time to keep
their prices down.

00:17:11.280 --> 00:17:15.135
And it's to me-- I'm not
always right in life.

00:17:15.135 --> 00:17:15.760
None of us are.

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:17.457
But I'm pretty close.

00:17:17.457 --> 00:17:18.290
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:17:18.290 --> 00:17:20.206
JON TAFFER: When it comes
to the bar business.

00:17:20.206 --> 00:17:23.770
People, when they stay with the
plan, tend to do really well.

00:17:23.770 --> 00:17:24.850
"Moon Runners"--

00:17:24.850 --> 00:17:25.599
MALE SPEAKER: Yup.

00:17:25.599 --> 00:17:27.599
JON TAFFER: Which is from
your neck of the wood.

00:17:27.599 --> 00:17:29.930
I mean, their
numbers are up 600%.

00:17:29.930 --> 00:17:32.300
And there's an independent
website-- forgive me,

00:17:32.300 --> 00:17:33.080
I forget the name.

00:17:33.080 --> 00:17:35.210
Bar Rescue something--
that somebody does,

00:17:35.210 --> 00:17:37.300
and they track them all.

00:17:37.300 --> 00:17:40.700
And I believe on their site--
and I haven't been there

00:17:40.700 --> 00:17:44.240
in a few weeks-- on their
site, we had aired 47 of 48.

00:17:44.240 --> 00:17:46.001
They claim that seven closed.

00:17:46.001 --> 00:17:46.750
And I don't count.

00:17:46.750 --> 00:17:48.470
So I'm going to take
them at face value.

00:17:48.470 --> 00:17:51.249
But what they did is they
did Before and After Yelp.

00:17:51.249 --> 00:17:53.290
And then they tell you if
it's opened and closed.

00:17:53.290 --> 00:17:55.350
So 48 or 49 episodes are there.

00:17:55.350 --> 00:17:58.040
If seven have
closed, that puts us

00:17:58.040 --> 00:17:59.726
in about an 80% track record.

00:17:59.726 --> 00:18:02.350
And when you consider the depth
of failure these people are in,

00:18:02.350 --> 00:18:03.510
I'm pretty proud of that.

00:18:03.510 --> 00:18:06.009
I'm not sure we could do much
better, to tell you the truth.

00:18:06.009 --> 00:18:08.147
But the pirates episode
has to be mentioned.

00:18:08.147 --> 00:18:08.980
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:18:08.980 --> 00:18:12.460
JON TAFFER: Only because it
was the most bizarre experience

00:18:12.460 --> 00:18:13.420
of my life.

00:18:13.420 --> 00:18:15.840
These people were pirates.

00:18:15.840 --> 00:18:18.760
They couldn't speak un-pirate.

00:18:18.760 --> 00:18:20.760
They couldn't talk like we do.

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:23.097
They spoke like 1845 pirates.

00:18:23.097 --> 00:18:23.930
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:18:23.930 --> 00:18:26.710
JON TAFFER: They didn't
have regular clothes.

00:18:26.710 --> 00:18:30.090
These people woke up every
morning to be pirates.

00:18:30.090 --> 00:18:33.490
And when I said to them how
how do you make a living?

00:18:33.490 --> 00:18:34.860
Oh, Renaissance Faire.

00:18:34.860 --> 00:18:36.180
That's two weeks a year.

00:18:36.180 --> 00:18:37.910
Oh, no, there's a
big pirate community.

00:18:37.910 --> 00:18:38.740
I go on Facebook.

00:18:38.740 --> 00:18:40.080
200 people.

00:18:40.080 --> 00:18:42.480
And these people
wanted to be pirates.

00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:44.820
And if you remember, when I
put them in regular clothes,

00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:47.370
they couldn't speak non-pirate.

00:18:47.370 --> 00:18:51.190
So I guess let them play in
their sandbox, so to speak.

00:18:51.190 --> 00:18:54.340
But that was a very
frustrating one for me,

00:18:54.340 --> 00:18:57.287
because a Discovery TV
was right next door.

00:18:57.287 --> 00:18:59.370
There were huge office
buildings in Silver Spring.

00:18:59.370 --> 00:19:02.800
The concept that we created
was for lunch and happy hour,

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:05.140
for them to close
early, because at night,

00:19:05.140 --> 00:19:07.280
that was a dangerous,
not a very good area.

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:09.790
They never even
opened for lunch.

00:19:09.790 --> 00:19:13.100
They tore the sign down
six hours after I left.

00:19:13.100 --> 00:19:14.150
It's on YouTube.

00:19:14.150 --> 00:19:17.550
A vigil around a fire, where
they were chanting, of course,

00:19:17.550 --> 00:19:19.280
pirate songs.

00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:23.186
And it was one of the most
bizarre experiences of my life.

00:19:23.186 --> 00:19:24.100
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:19:24.100 --> 00:19:25.820
JON TAFFER: I will
never forget it.

00:19:25.820 --> 00:19:27.640
And they're still
open, by the way,

00:19:27.640 --> 00:19:29.902
which is unbelievable to me.

00:19:29.902 --> 00:19:32.360
MALE SPEAKER: So you actually
kind of just referenced this.

00:19:32.360 --> 00:19:33.380
I know a couple
people in the crowd

00:19:33.380 --> 00:19:34.713
had asked me this ahead of time.

00:19:34.713 --> 00:19:36.220
But a lot of people
watch your show,

00:19:36.220 --> 00:19:38.320
and then they get on Yelp
immediately following,

00:19:38.320 --> 00:19:40.960
and see whether it's
been successful or not.

00:19:40.960 --> 00:19:43.780
And several times, we've seen
them change the name back.

00:19:43.780 --> 00:19:45.670
They reverted back
to their bad ways.

00:19:45.670 --> 00:19:47.430
Other people have
kept what you've

00:19:47.430 --> 00:19:48.680
done or remained successful.

00:19:48.680 --> 00:19:50.300
Can you kind of
talk about why is it

00:19:50.300 --> 00:19:51.790
that some have
reverted and failed,

00:19:51.790 --> 00:19:53.800
while others keep what
you've given them, et cetera.

00:19:53.800 --> 00:19:55.202
JON TAFFER: Yeah, good question.

00:19:55.202 --> 00:19:57.035
These people make
thousands of bad decisions

00:19:57.035 --> 00:19:58.466
that got me there.

00:19:58.466 --> 00:19:59.360
Right?

00:19:59.360 --> 00:20:01.490
Think of all the
choices that they

00:20:01.490 --> 00:20:04.580
made from hiring to
products to management

00:20:04.580 --> 00:20:07.550
to cause them to be in
the depth of failure

00:20:07.550 --> 00:20:09.900
that they're in when I show up.

00:20:09.900 --> 00:20:14.589
And my challenge is
to reverse that level

00:20:14.589 --> 00:20:16.005
of failure, that
depth of failure.

00:20:16.005 --> 00:20:17.055
I forgot your question.

00:20:17.055 --> 00:20:18.430
MALE SPEAKER: Oh,
it was just why

00:20:18.430 --> 00:20:20.440
do some revert back to their
old name and [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:20.440 --> 00:20:22.565
JON TAFFER: So what happens
is-- and I'll pick one.

00:20:22.565 --> 00:20:24.450
The Brixton in Austin, Texas.

00:20:24.450 --> 00:20:25.200
Remember that one?

00:20:25.200 --> 00:20:28.350
With the cocky husband--
they changed the name back

00:20:28.350 --> 00:20:29.330
a week later.

00:20:29.330 --> 00:20:30.740
But they kept everything else.

00:20:30.740 --> 00:20:32.160
They kept the
infusion cocktails.

00:20:32.160 --> 00:20:33.840
But they were hung
up on The Brixton.

00:20:33.840 --> 00:20:35.230
They're doing pretty well.

00:20:35.230 --> 00:20:37.030
But guys, you know this.

00:20:37.030 --> 00:20:40.990
If the Google name had
a terrible association

00:20:40.990 --> 00:20:43.640
with it and a reputation
for not delivering

00:20:43.640 --> 00:20:46.890
on the promises made, how much
advertising would you sell?

00:20:46.890 --> 00:20:48.430
So if I didn't
change the company,

00:20:48.430 --> 00:20:50.530
but put a new sign
on the building,

00:20:50.530 --> 00:20:52.850
at least I have a
chance at a new future.

00:20:52.850 --> 00:20:57.540
So, Swanky Bubbles--
remember that one?

00:20:57.540 --> 00:20:59.790
Who puts Swanky Bubbles
back on a building.

00:20:59.790 --> 00:21:02.090
You think you would thank
you for taking it down.

00:21:02.090 --> 00:21:04.210
But they changed the
name back the next day.

00:21:04.210 --> 00:21:06.760
And his logic was
it's confusing.

00:21:06.760 --> 00:21:10.250
My old customers won't
come to the new bar.

00:21:10.250 --> 00:21:12.310
You were losing money
with the old customers.

00:21:12.310 --> 00:21:14.624
And here's what they
don't understand.

00:21:14.624 --> 00:21:16.290
When they changed the
name back, they're

00:21:16.290 --> 00:21:18.700
thinking of the
customers they have.

00:21:18.700 --> 00:21:22.480
I'm trying to get them to
customers they don't have

00:21:22.480 --> 00:21:25.780
and the thousands of people that
they alienated and chased away.

00:21:25.780 --> 00:21:28.660
So with a new brand
comes a honeymoon.

00:21:28.660 --> 00:21:31.080
With a new brand comes
a whole new future.

00:21:31.080 --> 00:21:34.689
I have probably kept as
many brands as I've changed.

00:21:34.689 --> 00:21:36.730
So I don't just go in
there and change the brand.

00:21:36.730 --> 00:21:38.021
We do a lot of market research.

00:21:38.021 --> 00:21:39.410
I use Esri.

00:21:39.410 --> 00:21:41.000
And I do all my online research.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:43.551
By the way, "Bar Rescue"
is absolutely in real time.

00:21:43.551 --> 00:21:45.050
I should speak to
this for a moment.

00:21:45.050 --> 00:21:48.150
You know, the first day
I show up at about 4:35

00:21:48.150 --> 00:21:49.270
in the afternoon.

00:21:49.270 --> 00:21:51.291
I go in and do my
recon that night.

00:21:51.291 --> 00:21:53.540
When I leave the bar that
night, that day ends for me.

00:21:53.540 --> 00:21:54.456
I go back to my hotel.

00:21:54.456 --> 00:21:55.520
The next day is Day 2.

00:21:55.520 --> 00:21:57.190
We train, we have stress test.

00:21:57.190 --> 00:21:59.270
The next day is Day 3 training.

00:21:59.270 --> 00:22:02.370
At the end of Day 3,
at about 9 o'clock,

00:22:02.370 --> 00:22:04.350
I get the staff out
of there at night.

00:22:04.350 --> 00:22:07.060
And then we go to
work building the bar.

00:22:07.060 --> 00:22:09.710
We do it for a true 36 hours.

00:22:09.710 --> 00:22:12.710
So the evening of Day
3, the day of Day 4,

00:22:12.710 --> 00:22:15.510
and the morning of Day
5, we remodel the bar.

00:22:15.510 --> 00:22:18.150
And then I reveal
it to them on Day 5.

00:22:18.150 --> 00:22:21.245
It is absolutely in real
time, and not one word of it

00:22:21.245 --> 00:22:22.220
is scripted ever.

00:22:22.220 --> 00:22:24.560
Candidly, if it
was, I'd walk off.

00:22:24.560 --> 00:22:26.350
And I just won't do that.

00:22:26.350 --> 00:22:28.580
So it is incredibly real.

00:22:28.580 --> 00:22:31.990
And that's why the
casting, the selection

00:22:31.990 --> 00:22:34.450
of the bars and the
characters are so important,

00:22:34.450 --> 00:22:36.100
because I'm not
going to script it.

00:22:36.100 --> 00:22:36.780
And in "Bar

00:22:36.780 --> 00:22:40.010
Rescue," we use the phrase
"we work with what we have.

00:22:40.010 --> 00:22:42.680
We don't create
what we don't have."

00:22:42.680 --> 00:22:44.450
And it's working the moment.

00:22:44.450 --> 00:22:47.310
And we've gotten pretty good at
it, I think, after 59 of them

00:22:47.310 --> 00:22:48.120
or so.

00:22:48.120 --> 00:22:48.870
MALE SPEAKER: Man.

00:22:48.870 --> 00:22:52.054
So why did you decide
to write a book.

00:22:52.054 --> 00:22:54.220
JON TAFFER: I've been a
public speaker for 30 years.

00:22:54.220 --> 00:22:55.650
I love helping people.

00:22:55.650 --> 00:22:58.870
I can't tell you-- you know, I
tell people this story often.

00:22:58.870 --> 00:23:01.320
One of the greatest moments
in my life was an operator.

00:23:01.320 --> 00:23:03.450
When I opened Mall of
America, it had a dishwasher.

00:23:03.450 --> 00:23:05.280
His name was Theo.

00:23:05.280 --> 00:23:07.930
And this guy was a
dishwasher, almost

00:23:07.930 --> 00:23:10.580
a gang banger kind of
kid in Minneapolis.

00:23:10.580 --> 00:23:13.270
And my prep cook quit, and
I made him a prep cook.

00:23:13.270 --> 00:23:15.242
I liked this kid
for some reason.

00:23:15.242 --> 00:23:17.450
Then I'm opening another
restaurant six months later.

00:23:17.450 --> 00:23:19.930
And I pick a training
team from that restaurant

00:23:19.930 --> 00:23:21.580
and I fly them to another city.

00:23:21.580 --> 00:23:24.540
And I took Theo as
my prep cook trainee.

00:23:24.540 --> 00:23:27.500
And now we're in a hotel
meeting room, sort of like this.

00:23:27.500 --> 00:23:29.400
And all my training
team goes up in front

00:23:29.400 --> 00:23:31.630
of the staff to
introduce themselves.

00:23:31.630 --> 00:23:35.480
And Theo walks out there
in a shark skin suit,

00:23:35.480 --> 00:23:38.030
missing his teeth and
gold in the front,

00:23:38.030 --> 00:23:40.950
and says six months
ago, I was a dishwasher.

00:23:40.950 --> 00:23:42.850
And look at me today.

00:23:42.850 --> 00:23:44.160
And I cried.

00:23:44.160 --> 00:23:46.410
And I realized that was the
most important thing to me

00:23:46.410 --> 00:23:48.062
I could ever do.

00:23:48.062 --> 00:23:49.520
And I've been
fortunate in my life.

00:23:49.520 --> 00:23:50.800
I've made money.

00:23:50.800 --> 00:23:52.490
Now I want to make people.

00:23:52.490 --> 00:23:54.280
And I'm really inspired by that.

00:23:54.280 --> 00:23:55.750
And we talked
about this earlier,

00:23:55.750 --> 00:23:58.420
when people come up to me and
say they've gotten promoted,

00:23:58.420 --> 00:24:01.010
I've inspired them, they've
raised the bar, whatever

00:24:01.010 --> 00:24:03.500
it is it's an incredibly
motivating thing to me.

00:24:03.500 --> 00:24:05.880
So the book was an
effort to do that,

00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:09.080
to try to take what I do and
share it with more people,

00:24:09.080 --> 00:24:10.511
because I really believe in it.

00:24:10.511 --> 00:24:11.510
MALE SPEAKER: Very cool.

00:24:11.510 --> 00:24:14.090
And so your philosophy
of reaction management

00:24:14.090 --> 00:24:17.251
which you coined is kind of the
main theme throughout the book.

00:24:17.251 --> 00:24:19.500
Can you give everyone a quick
summary of what that is?

00:24:19.500 --> 00:24:21.110
JON TAFFER: Sure.

00:24:21.110 --> 00:24:22.942
First, let me explain
how it came about,

00:24:22.942 --> 00:24:24.900
because I don't cover it
very much in the book.

00:24:24.900 --> 00:24:27.108
When I was young, my mother
was incredibly difficult,

00:24:27.108 --> 00:24:28.490
a little violent.

00:24:28.490 --> 00:24:30.750
So when I was seven,
eight, nine, ten years old,

00:24:30.750 --> 00:24:34.545
I understood that if I
couldn't control her mood,

00:24:34.545 --> 00:24:36.990
I was going to
get my ass kicked.

00:24:36.990 --> 00:24:40.600
So at a very young age,
I learned the sensitivity

00:24:40.600 --> 00:24:43.670
to watch her face,
read her moods.

00:24:43.670 --> 00:24:49.510
And I developed this skill
to sense and feel people.

00:24:49.510 --> 00:24:52.120
Like your crossed arm, right?

00:24:52.120 --> 00:24:53.900
I would stare at you
and shake my head

00:24:53.900 --> 00:24:55.024
until those arms uncrossed.

00:24:55.024 --> 00:24:57.020
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:24:57.020 --> 00:24:58.620
JON TAFFER: Same with you.

00:24:58.620 --> 00:25:01.309
I mean, I look at
everybody's body language.

00:25:01.309 --> 00:25:02.350
And I do it subliminally.

00:25:02.350 --> 00:25:04.070
I don't think about
it consciously.

00:25:04.070 --> 00:25:06.640
Your eye contact, your body
language, your energy level,

00:25:06.640 --> 00:25:07.580
your posture.

00:25:07.580 --> 00:25:09.650
And I read these things.

00:25:09.650 --> 00:25:11.700
And I figured out how
to manipulate you.

00:25:11.700 --> 00:25:13.440
And here's a philosophy.

00:25:13.440 --> 00:25:15.610
If you go into a
restaurant and you sit down

00:25:15.610 --> 00:25:16.810
and you order food.

00:25:16.810 --> 00:25:19.540
And the food comes to the table,
and it's put down on a table.

00:25:19.540 --> 00:25:21.998
When the plate hits the table--
and this could be anything.

00:25:21.998 --> 00:25:25.360
It could be a Google ad--
one of two things happens.

00:25:25.360 --> 00:25:30.590
Either the guest sits up, reacts
to it, or nothing happens.

00:25:30.590 --> 00:25:33.250
If nothing happens, we're
stuck in mediocrity the rest

00:25:33.250 --> 00:25:34.630
of our lives.

00:25:34.630 --> 00:25:37.420
Whether that's a Google Ad,
whether it's a plate of food,

00:25:37.420 --> 00:25:40.510
whether it's a song, whether
it's the color of a wall,

00:25:40.510 --> 00:25:46.580
nothing we do is anything other
than creating human reactions.

00:25:46.580 --> 00:25:49.260
When reactions go in the
direction we want them to,

00:25:49.260 --> 00:25:52.254
people write us
checks, don't they?

00:25:52.254 --> 00:25:53.920
They move to other
sides of the country.

00:25:53.920 --> 00:25:55.040
They take jobs.

00:25:55.040 --> 00:25:57.580
Everything changes,
when we can cause

00:25:57.580 --> 00:26:00.250
people to react in the
ways that we need to.

00:26:00.250 --> 00:26:03.448
So at a young age, I
developed this skill.

00:26:03.448 --> 00:26:05.156
And that's why I think
"Bar Rescue" works

00:26:05.156 --> 00:26:07.322
for me because I'm only
with these people five days.

00:26:07.322 --> 00:26:08.530
I got to read them quick.

00:26:08.530 --> 00:26:10.920
And we were talking earlier--
I mean, I'm people's faces,

00:26:10.920 --> 00:26:13.760
for sure-- but
there's a reason why.

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:14.780
This might surprise you.

00:26:14.780 --> 00:26:16.690
I am never angry
on "Bar Rescue."

00:26:16.690 --> 00:26:18.660
It is completely calculated.

00:26:18.660 --> 00:26:20.310
It is completely deliberate.

00:26:20.310 --> 00:26:22.690
And we were talking, if
I wanted to pick on him,

00:26:22.690 --> 00:26:24.600
OK, this is a guy
with some pride.

00:26:24.600 --> 00:26:25.850
First, I'm going to try pride.

00:26:25.850 --> 00:26:27.230
Do you want to be a success?

00:26:27.230 --> 00:26:27.770
Do you want to be a failure?

00:26:27.770 --> 00:26:30.353
What are your parents going to
say when they see you faiiling?

00:26:30.353 --> 00:26:31.530
I'll try, that didn't work.

00:26:31.530 --> 00:26:32.512
Now, I'll try fear.

00:26:32.512 --> 00:26:33.845
You're going to lose everything!

00:26:33.845 --> 00:26:35.386
You're going to be
out in the street.

00:26:35.386 --> 00:26:37.000
What are you gon--
that didn't work.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:38.540
Picture your kids.

00:26:38.540 --> 00:26:39.900
Can you come true for your kids?

00:26:39.900 --> 00:26:40.710
That didn't work.

00:26:40.710 --> 00:26:42.779
Well, now I have
only one option.

00:26:42.779 --> 00:26:44.070
I'm going to rip you to shreds.

00:26:44.070 --> 00:26:45.390
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:26:45.390 --> 00:26:48.270
JON TAFFER: Because
I have no choice.

00:26:48.270 --> 00:26:49.490
I have no choice.

00:26:49.490 --> 00:26:53.980
And here is "Bar Rescue" in
its most essence, if you will,

00:26:53.980 --> 00:26:55.590
right at the core.

00:26:55.590 --> 00:26:57.740
You're going to
dig your heels in.

00:26:57.740 --> 00:26:59.790
And you're not
going to let me in.

00:26:59.790 --> 00:27:01.060
You're going to get defensive.

00:27:01.060 --> 00:27:02.780
So I'm going to be in your face.

00:27:02.780 --> 00:27:06.310
I am going to be
relentless, until I

00:27:06.310 --> 00:27:09.740
can make you doubt
yourself for one second.

00:27:09.740 --> 00:27:11.570
And if I can make
you doubt yourself

00:27:11.570 --> 00:27:13.930
just a little for one
second, your brain opens

00:27:13.930 --> 00:27:16.010
and I walk right the hell in.

00:27:16.010 --> 00:27:17.060
And that's the way it is.

00:27:17.060 --> 00:27:20.490
I got to break you down and
make you doubt yourself.

00:27:20.490 --> 00:27:22.080
Because you're the
one who's wrong.

00:27:22.080 --> 00:27:24.056
You're the one losing money.

00:27:24.056 --> 00:27:25.680
I've got the bank
accounts to prove it.

00:27:25.680 --> 00:27:28.620
So I stand there with
this cocky, confidence.

00:27:28.620 --> 00:27:31.550
And I will beat and
beat and beat on you

00:27:31.550 --> 00:27:33.690
until that crap comes open.

00:27:33.690 --> 00:27:36.270
And then I walk in, and we
were talking before I started,

00:27:36.270 --> 00:27:38.630
the biggest fights
I have are always

00:27:38.630 --> 00:27:41.730
the biggest hugs at
the end, aren't they?

00:27:41.730 --> 00:27:43.830
So when you turn them,
you really turn them.

00:27:43.830 --> 00:27:45.410
It's an incredible
thing to watch.

00:27:45.410 --> 00:27:48.580
And they walk different
four days later.

00:27:48.580 --> 00:27:51.229
Once I crack through,
their posture's different.

00:27:51.229 --> 00:27:52.770
Their facial expression
is different.

00:27:52.770 --> 00:27:54.436
When you look in your
eye, you can truly

00:27:54.436 --> 00:27:56.830
see this human transformation.

00:27:56.830 --> 00:27:58.150
It's remarkable.

00:27:58.150 --> 00:28:00.340
And you see it on TV, but
it's even more evident

00:28:00.340 --> 00:28:01.322
when you're there.

00:28:01.322 --> 00:28:02.246
MALE SPEAKER: Right.

00:28:02.246 --> 00:28:03.170
Very cool.

00:28:03.170 --> 00:28:05.630
So a lot of people in this
room work in advertising.

00:28:05.630 --> 00:28:07.290
You talk about
advertising in the book.

00:28:07.290 --> 00:28:09.710
Can you talk about what
sort of advertising bars

00:28:09.710 --> 00:28:13.490
can do from digital to-- you
talk a lot about word of mouth

00:28:13.490 --> 00:28:15.540
too, whether that can
be something generated.

00:28:15.540 --> 00:28:16.270
JON TAFFER: Sure.

00:28:16.270 --> 00:28:18.811
Let me start by saying I come
from an advertising background.

00:28:18.811 --> 00:28:21.410
My grandfather
invented Direct Mail.

00:28:21.410 --> 00:28:24.310
And gets credit for inventing
Direct Mail in Brooklyn, New

00:28:24.310 --> 00:28:24.810
York.

00:28:24.810 --> 00:28:27.720
When he was 16 years old,
he bought a printing press,

00:28:27.720 --> 00:28:29.455
and started putting
fliers in newspaper

00:28:29.455 --> 00:28:31.774
at the newspaper
stand on the corner.

00:28:31.774 --> 00:28:33.190
And then he walked
down the street

00:28:33.190 --> 00:28:35.340
and wrote down the
names in the mailboxes

00:28:35.340 --> 00:28:37.160
and started leaving
flyers in the apartment

00:28:37.160 --> 00:28:38.720
buildings in Brooklyn.

00:28:38.720 --> 00:28:41.070
And then, he started
getting and mailing them

00:28:41.070 --> 00:28:43.150
from this little
storefront that he had.

00:28:43.150 --> 00:28:45.240
And one of the largest
ad companies in the world

00:28:45.240 --> 00:28:47.900
knew we were advertising,
bought my grandfather's

00:28:47.900 --> 00:28:50.780
little storefront
operation, brought him in.

00:28:50.780 --> 00:28:53.780
The term Direct
Marketing was invented.

00:28:53.780 --> 00:28:57.450
And my grandfather then
created the entire direct

00:28:57.450 --> 00:28:58.980
marketing/direct mail.

00:28:58.980 --> 00:29:01.560
And my family has done
the direct marketing

00:29:01.560 --> 00:29:03.960
for Volvo, Mercedes Benz,
