00:48:38.990 --> 00:48:40.350
JON TAFFER: The show
pays for everything.

00:48:40.350 --> 00:48:41.530
The owner pays for nothing.

00:48:41.530 --> 00:48:43.720
AUDIENCE: And they're completely
separate once you leave?

00:48:43.720 --> 00:48:44.810
JON TAFFER: Yes, I
have no involvement

00:48:44.810 --> 00:48:46.018
in the business when I leave.

00:48:46.018 --> 00:48:48.420
As a matter of fact,
probably 80% of them,

00:48:48.420 --> 00:48:51.400
I've never spoken
with when I left.

00:48:51.400 --> 00:48:53.190
I will share my email with them.

00:48:53.190 --> 00:48:55.360
If they have questions,
they can shoot me an email.

00:48:55.360 --> 00:48:56.470
I give them my books.

00:48:56.470 --> 00:48:57.890
I give them lists of promotions.

00:48:57.890 --> 00:48:59.820
They get a binder
about this thick.

00:48:59.820 --> 00:49:01.330
And nine out of
ten of them never

00:49:01.330 --> 00:49:03.140
communicate with me ever again.

00:49:03.140 --> 00:49:05.030
And I don't look back,
to be honest with you.

00:49:05.030 --> 00:49:06.965
I'm always looking
forward at the next one.

00:49:06.965 --> 00:49:09.340
AUDIENCE: One of the best
things you ever did on the show

00:49:09.340 --> 00:49:12.740
was when you brought a previous
"Bar Rescue" owner in to spy

00:49:12.740 --> 00:49:13.936
for another one.

00:49:13.936 --> 00:49:15.060
That made a big impression.

00:49:15.060 --> 00:49:16.735
JON TAFFER: We're doing a
bunch of that this season.

00:49:16.735 --> 00:49:17.290
AUDIENCE: I hope so.

00:49:17.290 --> 00:49:19.170
JON TAFFER: It's fun
for me, because A, it

00:49:19.170 --> 00:49:21.207
gives you an update
on that bar when

00:49:21.207 --> 00:49:22.540
they tell you how they're doing.

00:49:22.540 --> 00:49:24.720
It shows the relationship
I created with them

00:49:24.720 --> 00:49:26.220
that it's real.

00:49:26.220 --> 00:49:28.030
And they went through
the experience,

00:49:28.030 --> 00:49:29.760
so they're great
candidates to do that.

00:49:29.760 --> 00:49:31.100
You're going to see a
lot of that this season.

00:49:31.100 --> 00:49:31.766
AUDIENCE: Great.

00:49:31.766 --> 00:49:32.490
Thank you.

00:49:32.490 --> 00:49:33.080
JON TAFFER: My pleasure.

00:49:33.080 --> 00:49:33.470
MALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:49:33.470 --> 00:49:35.636
So it's actually the last
question we have time for.

00:49:35.636 --> 00:49:39.440
Jon, do you have any other
final words or final advice

00:49:39.440 --> 00:49:40.400
for some of us?

00:49:40.400 --> 00:49:41.960
JON TAFFER: The
only final advice

00:49:41.960 --> 00:49:45.280
I would give you is I've lived
a very unconventional life.

00:49:45.280 --> 00:49:49.130
And it's because I live
my dream every day.

00:49:49.130 --> 00:49:51.170
Dreams are inspiring.

00:49:51.170 --> 00:49:53.040
Work is not.

00:49:53.040 --> 00:49:54.524
Find a dream.

00:49:54.524 --> 00:49:55.940
Whether it's that
client you can't

00:49:55.940 --> 00:49:59.460
get that you've been
fighting for six months.

00:49:59.460 --> 00:50:01.330
You got to have dreams.

00:50:01.330 --> 00:50:02.880
Dreams make this world go on.

00:50:02.880 --> 00:50:04.590
It built our whole country.

00:50:04.590 --> 00:50:08.700
And when we get in a
rut as human beings

00:50:08.700 --> 00:50:11.180
is when we lose touch
with our dreams.

00:50:11.180 --> 00:50:13.550
We lose the ability to
fight for those dreams.

00:50:13.550 --> 00:50:15.420
So don't be an
employee of Google.

00:50:15.420 --> 00:50:17.910
Live your dreams at Google.

00:50:17.910 --> 00:50:22.830
Find a way to match your dreams
with the goals of your company

00:50:22.830 --> 00:50:24.640
in your own work,
because there's

00:50:24.640 --> 00:50:29.320
nothing worse than mechanical
employees that lost touch

00:50:29.320 --> 00:50:30.950
with their dream.

00:50:30.950 --> 00:50:34.525
The other thing I would
say is leadership.

00:50:34.525 --> 00:50:36.150
I'm one of the few
people who say this.

00:50:36.150 --> 00:50:38.000
Leadership is not created.

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:40.040
You can read every
leadership book in the world.

00:50:40.040 --> 00:50:41.665
I can't make somebody
a leader, if they

00:50:41.665 --> 00:50:43.470
weren't by 12 years old.

00:50:43.470 --> 00:50:46.930
Leadership is a trait that we
have, that we're born with.

00:50:46.930 --> 00:50:48.430
The Pied Piper,
no, you never read

00:50:48.430 --> 00:50:50.069
what a good musician
he was, do you?

00:50:50.069 --> 00:50:52.360
Couldn't play the flute at
all, but people followed him

00:50:52.360 --> 00:50:53.693
off the cliff because of who is.

00:50:53.693 --> 00:50:55.830
How many entrepreneurs
do people follow

00:50:55.830 --> 00:50:58.850
to bankruptcy that don't
know what they're doing?

00:50:58.850 --> 00:51:01.600
Leadership is a
trait that is born.

00:51:01.600 --> 00:51:04.710
When you find a great leader,
attach yourself to him.

00:51:04.710 --> 00:51:07.490
Ride it to the end,
because great leadership

00:51:07.490 --> 00:51:11.190
and your dreams together will
take you to the Promised Land.

00:51:11.190 --> 00:51:13.410
And the worst thing
in the world is

00:51:13.410 --> 00:51:17.045
when you see somebody who
lost touch with their dreams.

00:51:17.045 --> 00:51:18.170
MALE SPEAKER: That's great.

00:51:18.170 --> 00:51:20.120
All right, a round of
applause for Jon Taffer.

00:51:20.120 --> 00:51:21.020
Thank you very much.

00:51:21.020 --> 00:51:26.743
AUDIENCE: [APPLAUSE]

